    "research-title": "Research",
    "research-ptsd-title": "Unveiling the Drivers of PTSD: An Interpretable Machine Learning Approach with SHAP",
    "research-ptsd-venue": "International Conference on Intelligent Computing and Data Analysis 2025 ; EI",
    "research-ptsd-tech-label": "Research & Technology",
    "research-ptsd-tech": "To deeply analyze PTSD influencing factors among 903 emergency responders, an interpretable machine learning architecture was employed. Constructed a Random Forest prediction model based on decision tree ensembles, and introduced SHAP (Shapley Additive exPlanations) and PDP (Partial Dependence Plots) to comprehensively deconstruct the black-box model, combined with Friedman H-statistic to profoundly validate complex non-linear interaction effects between variables.",
    "research-ptsd-result-label": "Findings & Conclusion",
    "research-ptsd-result": "Accurately quantified the buffering effect of psychological resilience on PTSD (SHAP value 0.5061) and keenly captured the U-shaped non-linear pattern in age distribution. The study not only verified deep interaction patterns among resilience, age, and trauma exposure but also provided data-driven differentiated intervention baselines for high-risk occupational groups.",
    "research-analysisposts-title": "Trustworthy Public Opinion Analysis Multi-Agent System",
    "research-analysisposts-venue": "Led multi-agent architecture design, focusing on black-box observability, long-horizon generation drift, and evidence traceability in open-domain agent systems.",
    "research-analysisposts-p1-label": "Multi-Agent Runtime & White-Box Observability",
    "research-analysisposts-p1": "Built a three-stage runtime across data preparation, collaborative analysis, and report generation on top of PocketFlow, and standardized statistical-analysis tools through MCP to reduce fragmented tool invocation, poor extensibility, and limited auditability in agent workflows. Also developed a Streamlit white-box console exposing step-level traces, tool I/O, and node scheduling paths, reducing exception diagnosis time for complex tasks from hours to 10 minutes.",
    "research-analysisposts-p2-label": "Collaborative Orchestration & Conflict Resolution",
    "research-analysisposts-p2": "Designed ForumHost as the explicit orchestration hub for open-domain public-opinion analysis, coordinating DataAgent for quantitative analysis over labeled data and tools, and SearchAgent for real-time facts and context via Tavily. Through iterative evidence supplementation, cross-challenge, conflict detection, and stopping conditions, the workflow constrained multi-agent collaboration from free-form dialogue into a controllable process and mitigated context pollution and objective drift. In representative head-to-head validation, key factual error rate dropped from about 20% to 0 versus a single-agent baseline using only DataAgent, and the factual portions of the final report required no further manual correction.",
    "research-analysisposts-p3-label": "Structured Reporting & Citation Constraints",
    "research-analysisposts-p3": "To address snowball hallucinations, unconstrained elaboration, and citation drift in long-horizon report generation, embedded structured output schemas, inline citations, source backtracking, and reliability annotations into chapter-by-chapter generation. Each core claim had to bind to evidence, source, and confidence score, with a verifier agent performing secondary checks on critical conclusions and cited evidence. Final reports reached 95% citation coverage, while incorrect citation rate was reduced to 3%.",
    "research-analysisposts-p4-label": "High-Concurrency Data Processing Pipeline",
    "research-analysisposts-p4": "Built an Async-based high-concurrency cleaning and semantic annotation pipeline for massive unordered raw posts. Few-shot prompted LLM nodes handled text cleaning, label completion, and semantic normalization, while retry logic, resumable execution, and concurrency control mitigated API rate limits and stabilized the data foundation for downstream analysis. Under a 40-60 concurrency budget, processing time for 20,000 records was reduced to under 12 hours, and input-token cost dropped by about 60% by caching few-shot examples and system prompts.",
